\par }\pard \sb200\sa100\sl360\slmult0 {\f4\fs32\cf1 What you need to use these programs
\par }\pard \li863\sa100\sl240\slmult0 {\f4\cf1 This Getting Started Guide assumes that you are already reasonably familiar with the way your computer works. If you are new to computing, or to Windows, you are advised to familiarise y
ourself both with the relevant terminology and the basics of using your computer. You\rquote ll need to know how to: 
\par }\pard \fi-216\li1080\sa100\sl240\slmult0\tx1080 {\f4\cf1 Start up programs and open documents;
\par Access a disc, view directories, and copy files; 
\par Display menus and choose entries from them; 
\par Position and resize windows, use the Program Manager, minimise and restore files (Windows)
\par Scroll through documents using the scroll bars and arrows;
\par Use the mouse to move the pointer around the screen and to display and position the caret, and how to use the mouse buttons to click, double-click and drag objects. 
\par }\pard \li863\sa100\sl240\slmult0 {\f4\cf1 You should also understand terms such as directory, double click, and dialogue box.
\par You\rquote ll find all this information in the Windows documentation which came with your computer. The tutorial chapters in the Getting Started Guide also provide a reminder of these skills.
